{"key":"post-8728016","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8728016</id>\n<content>5.5 is about normal for peat.&amp;nbsp; Use one teaspoon of hydrated lime per cup of peat to get in the ballpark. Make sure your hydrated lime has no more than 2% mg. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Gypsum is optional, but will improve performance in everything you grow mushrooms on, from grains to substrates and casing materials.&amp;nbsp; Use up to 10% gypsum by volume in casing layers and substrates, and a pinch between your thumb and forefinger for grain and brf tek jars(or follow the instructions in the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/Lets-Grow-Mushrooms-Marc-Keith/dp/B0011ZJ53G/ref=sr_1_13_s9_rk?ie=UTF8&amp;s=dvd&amp;s9r=8afd3cfe16c84afc011771946a900fb3&amp;itemPosition=13&amp;qid=1201908104&amp;sr=8-13&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;linkCode=ll1&amp;tag=theshro-20&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;Let's Grow Mushrooms&lt;/a&gt; DVD. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Here's the label of the right stuff, also from a 50 lb bag.&amp;nbsp; Make sure it says 'agricultural' hydrated lime.&amp;nbsp; Don't use masonry hydrated lime as it's loaded with magnesium. The second picture is a common brand found in nurseries and hardware stores.&lt;br /&gt;RR&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/06-29/352394956-hydrated_lime_label.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;/forums/thumbs/06-29/352394956-thumb_hydrated_lime_label.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/032303-8/89949-lime1.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;/forums/thumbs/032303-8/89949-thumb_lime1.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</conte